{"id":"1907.12486","submitter":"Nikita Nikulsin","authors":"Nikita Nikulsin, Matthias Hoelzl, Alessandro Zocco, Karl Lackner,\n  Sibylle G\\\"unter","title":"A three-dimensional reduced MHD model consistent with full MHD","comments":"18 pages. This article was published in Physics of Plasmas","journal-ref":"Phys. Plasmas 26, 102109 (2019)","doi":"10.1063/1.5122013","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.plasm-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Within the context of a viscoresistive magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) model with\nanisotropic heat transport and cross-field mass diffusion, we introduce novel\nthree-term representations for the magnetic field (background vacuum field,\nfield line bending and field compression) and velocity ($\\vec E\\times\\vec B$\nflow, field-aligned flow and fluid compression), which are amenable to\nthree-dimensional treatment. Once the representations are inserted into the MHD\nequations, appropriate projection operators are applied to Faraday's law and\nthe Navier-Stokes equation to obtain a system of scalar equations that is\nclosed by the continuity and energy equations. If the background vacuum field\nis sufficiently strong and the $\\beta$ is low, MHD waves are approximately\nseparated by the three terms in the velocity representation, with each term\ncontaining a specific wave. Thus, by setting the appropriate term to zero, we\neliminate fast magnetosonic waves, obtaining a reduced MHD model. We also show\nthat the other two velocity terms do not compress the magnetic field, which\nallows us to set the field compression term to zero within the same reduced\nmodel. Dropping also the field-aligned flow, a further simplified model is\nobtained, leading to a fully consistent hierarchy of reduced and full MHD\nmodels for 3D plasma configurations. Finally, we discuss the conservation\nproperties and derive the conditions under which the reduction approximation is\nvalid. We also show that by using an ordering approach, reduced MHD equations\nsimilar to what we got from the ansatz approach can be obtained by means of a\nphysics-based asymptotic expansion.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Jul 2019 15:36:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 5 Sep 2019 09:42:53 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 14 Oct 2019 15:11:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-15"}
{"id":"1907.12487","submitter":"Steven Touzard","authors":"P. Campagne-Ibarcq, A. Eickbusch, S. Touzard, E. Zalys-Geller, N.E.\n  Frattini, V.V. Sivak, P. Reinhold, S. Puri, S. Shankar, R.J. Schoelkopf, L.\n  Frunzio, M. Mirrahimi, M.H. Devoret","title":"Quantum error correction of a qubit encoded in grid states of an\n  oscillator","comments":"Text and figures edited for clarity. The claims of the paper remain\n  the same. Author list fixed","journal-ref":"Nature 584, 368-372 (2020)","doi":"10.1038/s41586-020-2603-3","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum bits are more robust to noise when they are encoded non-locally. In\nsuch an encoding, errors affecting the underlying physical system can then be\ndetected and corrected before they corrupt the encoded information. In 2001,\nGottesman, Kitaev and Preskill (GKP) proposed a hardware-efficient instance of\nsuch a qubit, which is delocalised in the phase-space of a single oscillator.\nHowever, implementing measurements that reveal error syndromes of the\noscillator while preserving the encoded information has proved experimentally\nchallenging: the only realisation so far relied on post-selection, which is\nincompatible with quantum error correction (QEC). The novelty of our experiment\nis precisely that it implements these non-destructive error-syndrome\nmeasurements for a superconducting microwave cavity. We design and implement an\noriginal feedback protocol that incorporates such measurements to prepare\nsquare and hexagonal GKP code states. We then demonstrate QEC of an encoded\nqubit with unprecedented suppression of all logical errors, in quantitative\nagreement with a theoretical estimate based on the measured imperfections of\nthe experiment. Our protocol is applicable to other continuous variable systems\nand, in contrast with previous implementations of QEC, can mitigate all logical\nerrors generated by a wide variety of noise processes, and open a way towards\nfault-tolerant quantum computation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Jul 2019 15:36:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 19 Mar 2020 03:09:41 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 23 Mar 2020 02:06:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-06"}
